e></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FH006788%2F1"><gtr:id>B42FAB92-2BD7-41F3-8312-92AE30C76308</gtr:id><gtr:title>Analysing Monetary Transmission Mechanisms and Equilibrium Exchange Rates in the UK and the Euro Area</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/H006788/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The first part of the project will analyse monetary policy transmission in the UK and the euro area. The model proposed evaluates the impact that monetary policy decisions have on macroeconomic variables, such as inflation and output, and estimates these variables' fundamental values&amp;nbsp;- the value when the economy is in equilibrium.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p>

&lt;p>The proposed technique would be useful for the Bank of England (BoE), European Central Bank (ECB) and HM Treasury in setting monetary and fiscal policies. The second part of the project will identify the equilibrium exchange rate between sterling and euro and their equilibrium effective exchange rates. The model proposed would be an interest for BoE, ECB, HM Treasury and the wider financial community.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The project is also relevant to the recent debate as to whether, in the medium to long-term, the UK should enter the euro area. Similarities in monetary transmission between these two economies will be assessed.&amp;nbsp; This is essential for judging whether the ECB could effectively mitigate inflation pressures and stabilise economic fluctuations in the UK and the euro area. Knowing the underlying equilibrium exchange rate between sterling and euro helps to determine an appropriate entry exchange rate if the UK were to join the euro.&lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2011-09-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>147285</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>14081279-8EED-4F60-BEB4-71A24D86461A</gtr:id><gtr:title>Asset prices, credit and the business cycle</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Economics Letters</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/7771ec39b9bd63d704f50fabca5f24ae"><gtr:id>7771ec39b9bd63d704f50fabca5f24ae</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Chen X</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2012-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>doi_53cf8ff8fef1ea16</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>3F9909F9-04DD-4D8A-89B9-3079CD4280F9</gtr:id><gtr:title>Realized and Optima